docs.abstract: And what else you need to know today.
docs.snippet: And what else you need to know today.
docs.lead_paragraph: It can often feel like nothing changes with police killings. Gruesome, high-profile cases keep coming — Eric Garner, Michael Brown, Freddie Gray, Breonna Taylor, George Floyd, now Manuel Ellis — and the annual number of killings nationwide remains at about 1,100.

docs.abstract: The rocker’s wine is featured in a new picnic to-go from the rooftop bar Versa in Midtown.
docs.snippet: The rocker’s wine is featured in a new picnic to-go from the rooftop bar Versa in Midtown.
docs.lead_paragraph: Picnicking is an easy socially distant gathering for lunch or dinner. Versa, a rooftop bar and restaurant atop the Renaissance New York Midtown hotel, has assembled picnic baskets that can be ordered for delivery on Saturdays or Sundays to eight Manhattan parks, including Bryant Park, the Sheep Meadow and the Mall in Central Park and Hudson River Park. The basic $35 menu consists of a lobster roll from the Lobster Place in Chelsea Market, a bottle of Evian, a face mask and a bottle of Hampton Water, a pale, floral French rosé developed by Jesse Bongiovi and his father, Jon Bon Jovi, in partnership with the winemaker Gérard Bertrand. For $85, you also get an antipasto platter of charcuterie, cheeses, fruit, flatbread and smoked salmon, and some hand sanitizer. At $135, there are two lobster rolls and two bottles of wine and water, a tote bag and a picnic blanket, along with the other items. Versa and Hampton Water are donating to Black Lives Matter and other charities. Delivery is included. Orders must be placed by 5 p.m. Fridays.

headline.print_headline: To Enjoy: Picnic While Sipping A Rocker’s Rosé

docs.abstract: Shows of support from Facebook, Twitter and YouTube don’t address the way those platforms have been weaponized by racists and partisan provocateurs.
docs.snippet: Shows of support from Facebook, Twitter and YouTube don’t address the way those platforms have been weaponized by racists and partisan provocateurs.
docs.lead_paragraph: Several weeks ago, as protests erupted across the nation in response to the police killing of George Floyd, Mark Zuckerberg wrote a long and heartfelt post on his Facebook page, denouncing racial bias and proclaiming that “black lives matter.” Mr. Zuckerberg, Facebook’s chief executive, also announced that the company would donate $10 million to racial justice organizations.

headline.main: Social Media Giants Support Racial Justice. Their Products Undermine It.
headline.print_headline: Platforms Denounce Racism That Thrives There

docs.abstract: The Museum of Food and Drink has added a BLM Community Resources page to its website, along with a preview of its new “African/American” exhibition.
docs.snippet: The Museum of Food and Drink has added a BLM Community Resources page to its website, along with a preview of its new “African/American” exhibition.
docs.lead_paragraph: BLM Community Resources, on the website for the Museum of Food and Drink, lists scores of black-owned farms, restaurants, food resources in black communities and charities. Among them are a flower farm that Walker Marsh developed on what was an empty lot in Baltimore, and a fund-raiser for the family of David McAtee, the barbecue chef who was shot and killed this month in Louisville, Ky. The museum is asking for public opinion as the webpage evolves. The website also has a preview of “African/American: Making the Nation’s Table,” an exhibition that has been postponed.

headline.main: Ways to Support Black Farmers, Restaurants and Nonprofits
headline.print_headline: To Donate: BLM Resources Added To Museum Website

docs.abstract: The president tweeted to say it was disrespectful to kneel during the national anthem, as Colin Kaepernick and other players began doing in 2016 to protest racial injustice. N.F.L. Commissioner Roger Goodell then said the league supported players peacefully protesting.
docs.snippet: The president tweeted to say it was disrespectful to kneel during the national anthem, as Colin Kaepernick and other players began doing in 2016 to protest racial injustice. N.F.L. Commissioner Roger Goodell then said the league supported players ...
docs.lead_paragraph: The protracted debate in the N.F.L. over players protesting racial injustice during the national anthem reignited with force on Friday as President Trump rekindled his war with the league over the issue and the league’s commissioner, Roger Goodell, issued his strongest support yet for the players seeking to fight racism and police brutality.

headline.main: As Trump Rekindles N.F.L. Fight, Goodell Sides With Players
